description:
Founded in 1909 by magician Albert Carlton Gilbert (1884-1961) the company sold products for magicians. He soon started manufacturing and selling toys. His best seller the Erector Set (similar to Meccano), which he developed himself, sold over 30 million units by 1935. During his 50 year career he acquired over 150 patents. Most of them on educational toys. As most wartime companies Gilbert started producing equipment for the war effort. They produced aircraft equipment from 1942 until the war ended.

Gilbert was at one point the larges toy producing company in the United States, maybe even the world. They sold the Erector sets, American Flyer, chemistry sets, microscope kits and even James Bond movie figures and the Aston Martin DB5. Next to their toy line they also produced small home appliance.

The company employed more than 5000 people in round the clock shifts and that made the company the largest in New Haven from the 30's to 50's.

In the 50's the company produced two promotional comic books that tell a story of how many professionals working on projects of great importance to our future got the passion for their careers playing with a Gilbert Science Kit years earlier.

After the founder A.C. Gilbert died at the age of 76 in 1961 and the company came under leadership of Alberts son Al it struggled to keep it's head above water. It finally went bankrupt in 1967 after the Gilbert family members sold their shares to Jack Wrather who also couldn't turn the tide on the profitability of the company. As so often happens when a family firm turns over leadership to the 2nd generation, it ran itself into the ground. Not only because of bad leadership but also the bad economic conditions and Al was never the man his father was as far as inventing new ways to bring science to the kids. And his father had never really got Al ready for succession of himself.

After the bankruptcy a couple of toy lines like American Flyer, the microscope sets and Erector were sold to other companies that continued to use the A.C. Gilbert Company name and logo on the boxes long after the company had met it's demise.
name: A. C. Gilbert Co.
